'"The sea is ours": Bolivia with no outlet on the sea hopes that a court will reopen the path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a naval headquarters covered in rigging in La Paz.
Public buildings display an ocean blue flag.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon River are decorated with the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
It's a duty to get it back."
Throughout the landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the lost coast and now in the hands of Chile after a bloody conflict over the resources of the 19th century is still alive, as is the desire to cross the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have perhaps reached the highest level in decades, while Bolivia awaits the decision of the International Court of Justice on 1 October after five years of deliberations.
" Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and is obviously waiting for the result with a positive attitude," explained Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the judgment of the International Court of Justice on large screens throughout the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will welcome Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent dialogue, Chile should be obliged to negotiate, guaranteeing Bolivia an outlet on the sea that is the responsibility of the State.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president - who is facing a controversial battle for reelection next year - has a lot at stake with Monday's ruling.
"We are very close to our return to the Pacific Ocean," he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that the court will hardly decide in favor of Bolivia and that little would change if it did.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no power to allocate Chilean territory and has specified that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the ruling of the International Court of Justice comes just six months after the final arguments indicates that the case ‘was not complicated’, said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from advancing the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have delayed it.
"The problem of access to the sea has been monopolized by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
Morale's belligerent rhetoric has broken any good intentions remaining in Chile, he suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue the negotiations at some point, but it will be very difficult to maintain the discussions as a result of what has happened.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making process was particularly swift.
On Monday Bolivia will be able "to enjoy extraordinary opportunities in relations with Chile" and will have the opportunity to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual advantage", he explained.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales - one of the most popular presidents of Latin America - is using the maritime issue as a political eschatage.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The sentence is an opportunity to see that we need to overcome the past."
