John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective efforts.
With over 30,000 pupils throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for subsequent higher education, their chosen career and place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector capable of developing and adopting a personalised school study plan, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and required subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language that he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will come to the heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on the English alone if we want to build trust relations with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
68% of pupils who studied foreign languages got the highest grade.
The data, collected by the 74 schools member of SCIS, showed that 72% of students got the highest vote with praise in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish got the maximum vote.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as key competences for children and young people, who will no doubt need them in the future.
Currently languages, as a choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in the study plans of independent institutions and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons that employees have indicated for the difficulty in covering jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
For this reason language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a lifelong competence like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically bring a multilingual person to the forefront of competition.
According to a survey by YouGov among over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a sufficient level to be able to hold a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, particularly those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK by looking at 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with the teaching staff specialized in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed for success, whatever their future.
It is not possible to deny at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
The faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
