"However, we do not see any consistent response from the US," he said.
"Without confidence in the US there will be no security in our national security, and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
Although Mr Ri has re-used the complaint concerning Washington's resistance to a denuclearization "in stages" with which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not entirely reject unilateral denuclearization as previously done by Pyongyang.
He referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first absolute meeting between a US President in office and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim committed to working towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees to North Korean security.
North Korea sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also opposed calls to ease the strict international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on the need for "first denuclearisation" and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose coercively and even oppose the "declaration of the end of the war", said Ri.
"The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who don't know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust."
Ri did not refer to programs of a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader had announced to the UN at the beginning of the week.
The minister instead underlined the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last 5 months and added: "If the counterpart of this question of denuclearization were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this point dead."
But even so, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from that of last year at the UN General Assembly, when he stated that it was inevitable to target the U.S. territory with North Korea missiles after "the president of evil" Trump had called Kim a "missile man" engaged in a suicide mission.
Before the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "destroy completely" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to embark on the path of disarmament, but stated that much still needs to be done and that sanctions will remain in place until North Korea's denuclearisation.
Wednesday Trump said he didn't have a deadline, saying that "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
