The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own "personal data store online" or a POD.
It can include lists of contacts, to-dos, calendars, music libraries and other personal and professional tools.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available on one browser and at the same time.
The uniqueness of the warehouse of personal data online is that it is completely at the user's choice who can have access to what type of information.
The company calls it "personal enhancement through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to John Bruce, CEO of the company, is to provide adequate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, some developers in the staff hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology programmers from all over the world will be able to create their own decentralised apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team will not tell "Facebook and Google whether or not to introduce a complete change where their business models are completely wiped out overnight.
"We're not asking their permission."
In a post on Medium published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to procure commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web built from Solid".
In 1994 Berners-Lee transformed the internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months Berners-Lee has represented an influential voice in the debate on net neutrality.
Even after the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the Founder and Manager of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
