the new military ship of Germany is postponed again
According to local media, the last frigate of the German Navy should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace the old military ships of the Cold War times, but there will not be at least until next year due to faulty systems and a surge in costs.
The commission of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the flagship of the new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit citing a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but worrying issues after delivery tormented the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old ships of the Bremen class.
They will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some hidden technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, in fact it should be possible to employ new frigates up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continuous delays imply that the innovative warships, which are said to allow Germany to project its power overseas, will already become obsolete when they enter service, notes the Die Zeit.
The unfortunate frigate Type F-125 made news last year, when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy returned a ship to the builder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media noticed a number of crucial "software and hardware defects" that made the ship useless when employed on a combat mission.
The deficiencies in the software were particularly important as the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be managed by a crew of about 120 sailors, just half the staff of the oldest ships in the Bremen class.
