The National Trust is spying on the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highland estate aims to reveal the way bats use sight to procure food.
It is hoped that discoveries can shed light on the behavior of the only flying mammals in existence and guide future protection activities.
The study of the scientists of the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and soprano, in addition to the brown mumps and bats of Daubenton at the Inverewe Gardens, in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key places around the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using portable detectors.
Analysis of sounds recorded by an expert will determine the frequency of bat calls and the way each species behaves.
A habitat map and a relationship will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviour on a scale.
Rob Dewar, nature protection consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results can reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, and how best to maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has decreased considerably in the last century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development works that affect trespolis and ruin the habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than the eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique to detect insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts conduct regular investigations, inspect the trespolis and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organization has even established the first reserve of Scotland intended solely for bats at the Threeve estate, in the region of Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of bats of Scotland.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says that the property is the ideal territory.
"Here in Threeave we have a large area for bats," he said.
"We have ancient buildings, many secular trees and a good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats that we don't know yet, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs."
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before conducting maintenance within the properties as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternal trespole can kill up to 400 females and small, possibly sweeping away an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their trespolis.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations are doing".
