Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in the concentration of red tide in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patched flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier.
The red tidal bloom extends for about 130 miles of coast from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The patches are about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in less areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coast, a low to high concentration off the Hillsborough County, a background concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, a background concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coast, a background concentration to an average concentration in Charlotte County, a background concentration to a high concentration in Lee County or off its coast and a low concentration in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
While last week no case was reported in northwest Florida.
